               <FONT COLOR="blue" SIZE="+3"><B>Step-by-Step Instructions...</B></FONT>

<P>This guide covers the installation of Chimera&nbsp;2.0 step-by-step.</P>

<H3><A HREF="serverdocs.html">1. Installing the Server Documentation</A></H3>

<P>This section covers the installation of the HTML documentation for Chimera&nbsp;2.0's hypermedia servers.</P>

<P><B>Note:</B> This documentation does not cover the server's application program interface. We will be releasing javadoc-generated HTML documentation in the near future to cover the server APIs.</P>

<P>This page currently under construction.</P>

<!--
<H3>Installing the Class Files</H3>

<OL>
<LI>Place the <tt>chimera.jar</tt> file in the same directory in which
you store other third-party java applications and libraries.
<LI>Add <tt>chimera.jar</tt> to your <tt>CLASSPATH</tt> environment
variable.
</OL>

<H3>Installing the Source Code</H3>

<OL>
<LI>Place the source code archive (either <tt>chimera.2.0.alpha.tar.gz</tt> or
<tt>chimera.2.0.alpha.zip</tt>) in a directory where you store the source
code for third-party Java applications and libraries.
<LI>Ensure that no directories within this directory are
named <tt>chimera</tt>.
<LI>Uncompress the archive.
    <UL>
        <LI>For the former use,
        <tt>gzip -d chimera.2.0.alpha.tar.gz; tar xvf chimera.2.0.alpha.tar</tt>
        <LI>For the latter use, <tt>unzip chimera.2.0.alpha.zip</tt>
    </UL>
<LI>Delete the archive file.
</OL>

<H3>Compiling the Source Code (optional)</H3>

<P>
Make files are included in this release to help compile the source code
under Solaris. (To compile the source code on other platforms, let
the root makefile serve as a guide on what needs to be compiled.
More detailed instructions for other platforms will be made available
in future releases.)
</P>

<OL>
<LI>Ensure that the JFC is available in your CLASSPATH.
<LI>Execute the makefile in the root directory. Note: The makefile
makes use of the -d flag of the javac compiler to place the class
files generated during compilation in a separate directory. You
will need to modify the makefile to specify a directory in which
to place the .class files. The directory that you specify needs to
be in your CLASSPATH. The compile will produce a chimera subdirectory
in the specified directory.
<LI>The compile will fail on some files the first time you run it. It should
compile fine on the second pass.
</OL>

<H3>Installing the C API (optional)</H3>

<P>
If you want to develop C-based Chimera 2.0 clients, you will need to
install the Chimera 2.0 C API.
</P>

<OL>
<LI>Create a new directory for the C API.
<LI>Place the C API Archive, <tt>capi.tar.gz</tt>, in the directory.
<LI>Extract the files from the archive using
<tt>gzip -d capi.tar.gz; tar xvf capi.tar</tt>.
<LI>Edit the Makefile and change the value for the X11_INCLUDE variable.
<LI>Invoke <tt>make</tt>.
</OL>

<I>Note the instructions above assume that the X11 library directory is
already a part of your LD_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable. If this
is not the case and you experience problems creating the C API library,
be sure to add the X11 lib directory to the LD_LIBRARY_PATH.</I>

<P>
At this point you may want to download some of the example C-based clients
to explore the use of the C API.
</P>-->
